{"key":"processedPost-15700951","value":{"id":15700951,"first":15700123,"last":15702427,"when":1327246404,"utime":"01/22/12 05:33 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Icesyn said:</b><br /><br />As for the isolating, MS isn't where I would start. After you isolated a bunch of different genomes, you would have to test the strains to see what specimen produces the best. I would avoid that and just clone from the fruit (naturally isolated and is the result if other grows are replicated precisely)<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Incorrect.&nbsp; If one is isolating strains, numerous spores are required to get the most genetic diversity.&nbsp; Cloning a fruit from a flush is NOT isolating strains, and fruits can have many strains active in a single fruitbody.&nbsp; When you clone it, you only get one of those strains, and may not preserve the genetics.<br /><br />An inoculating loop can easily be made with very thin wire.&nbsp; Use VERY thin wire so it cools down faster after heating red hot.&nbsp; A paper clip will remain hot for a long time, and can kill your spores.<br /><br />Watch the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Strain-Isolation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">strain isolation on agar video clip</a> before starting.&nbsp; It's just a sample clip-the whole tek is on the DVD.<br />RR","title":"Re: Isolate supplies and technique questions? Yes I'm needy..","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}